<TITLE>NPVIC is a bad idea</TITLE>


<TEXT>
I have some thoughts on the National Popular Vote Interstate Compact. 
 
In the <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE" value="2016">2016</TIMEX3> election, roughly 70 percent of West Virginians <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">voted</EVENT> for Trump. Had the NPVIC been in effect, W.Va. electors would have been <EVENT eid="e2" class="I_STATE">required</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE">cast</EVENT> their votes for Hillary Clinton because she <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE">won</EVENT> the nationwide popular <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">vote</EVENT>. The same would be true in all the states Trump <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">carried</EVENT>. The NPVIC would have <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">made</EVENT> electors puppets of Clinton and the Democratic Party. 
 
Thankfully, the NPVIC was not in effect in <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DATE" value="2016">2016</TIMEX3>. 
 
We <EVENT eid="e8" class="I_ACTION">elect</EVENT> our members of congress and senators to <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">represent</EVENT> us in Washington. We should <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE">choose</EVENT> our electors to <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE">do</EVENT> the same in the Electoral College. If electors arent free to <EVENT eid="e12" class="OCCURRENCE">represent</EVENT> their constituents, why have electors? Why have an Electoral College? 
 
The Electoral College concept reflects our founding fathers concerns with separation of powers and checks and balances to <EVENT eid="e13" class="I_STATE">prevent</EVENT> a <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DATE" value="FUTURE_REF">future</TIMEX3> tyranny in our country. That is the reason they <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">gave</EVENT> the individual states so much power and latitude in the <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">selection</EVENT> of their electors and the rules concerning how electors vote. 
 
The NPVIC <EVENT eid="e16" class="OCCURRENCE">negates</EVENT> those separations of powers and checks and balances by <EVENT eid="e17" class="OCCURRENCE">shifting</EVENT> the power to <EVENT eid="e18" class="OCCURRENCE">decide</EVENT> elections into the blue state population centers and <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE">leaving</EVENT> rural red states out of the process. 
 
<EVENT eid="e20" class="OCCURRENCE">Allowing</EVENT> too much power in the hand of any one individual, political group or area of the country is a form of tyranny. 
 
The , period. 
 
In his <TIMEX3 tid="t4" type="DATE" value="2017-01-15">Jan. 15 letter</TIMEX3>, Ralph Chambers correctly <EVENT eid="e21" class="I_STATE">states</EVENT> Congress shall <EVENT eid="e22" class="OCCURRENCE">make</EVENT> no law <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE">respecting</EVENT> the establishment of a religion or <EVENT eid="e24" class="I_ACTION">prohibiting</EVENT> the free exercise thereof <EVENT eid="e25" class="OCCURRENCE">appears</EVENT> in the First Amendment. 
 
Mr. Chambers graciously <EVENT eid="e26" class="OCCURRENCE">makes</EVENT> my case for me. No where is the term separation of church and state <EVENT eid="e27" class="OCCURRENCE">mentioned</EVENT> in the Constitution. 
 
The term separation of church and state was <EVENT eid="e28" class="OCCURRENCE">coined</EVENT> in <TIMEX3 tid="t5" type="DATE" value="196X">the 1960s</TIMEX3> when liberal judges <EVENT eid="e29" class="OCCURRENCE">began</EVENT> their <EVENT eid="e30" class="OCCURRENCE">attacks</EVENT> on our religious freedoms by <EVENT eid="e31" class="OCCURRENCE">banning</EVENT> prayer and Bible <EVENT eid="e32" class="OCCURRENCE">reading</EVENT> in public schools. Those <EVENT eid="e33" class="OCCURRENCE">decisions</EVENT> should be made by parents, local schools and local officials, not the federal government. 
 
Since then, nativity scenes have been <EVENT eid="e34" class="OCCURRENCE">banned</EVENT> from public squares, <EVENT eid="e35" class="OCCURRENCE">praying</EVENT> before football games, even <EVENT eid="e36" class="REPORTING">saying</EVENT> Merry <TIMEX3 tid="t6" type="DATE" value="X">Christmas</TIMEX3> is <EVENT eid="e37" class="OCCURRENCE">forbidden</EVENT> for fear of <EVENT eid="e38" class="OCCURRENCE">offending</EVENT> some atheist. 
 
<TIMEX3 tid="t7" type="DATE" value="PRESENT_REF">Now</TIMEX3> one atheist can <EVENT eid="e39" class="OCCURRENCE">restrict</EVENT> the free exercise of religion by the majority. 
 
What part of <EVENT eid="e40" class="OCCURRENCE">prohibiting</EVENT> the free exercise thereof cant liberals <EVENT eid="e41" class="OCCURRENCE">understand</EVENT>? 
 
Steve Wolverton 
 
Parkersburg
</TEXT>


